<div id="review_1228683636" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1228683636" />
    <a title="Jenn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5745637-jenn"><img alt="Jenn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1425601760p2/5745637.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1228683636?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenn" href="/user/show/5745637-jenn">Jenn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5745637-jenn?shelf=netgalley-arc-reviews">netgalley-arc-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5745637-jenn?shelf=series-finished">series-finished</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5745637-jenn?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1228683636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7405339985745948912"><br/>This series has put me through so many wild emotions. Starting out Slave was one of the first books that I had ever read with the sub/dom and even rescue element. And it rocked my world and my emotions of love and anger were reeling for days. This book didn&apos;t quite hit that high mark, but the author tied up the endings for the most part smoothly.<br/><br/>Minor spoilers ahead.<br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[<br/>The final book still touched on these ideas, but it began to turn the focus to more of the need for justice in Brian</span></span>
  <span id="freeText7405339985745948912" style="display:none"><br />This series has put me through so many wild emotions. Starting out Slave was one of the first books that I had ever read with the sub/dom and even rescue element. And it rocked my world and my emotions of love and anger were reeling for days. This book didn't quite hit that high mark, but the author tied up the endings for the most part smoothly.<br /><br />Minor spoilers ahead.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />The final book still touched on these ideas, but it began to turn the focus to more of the need for justice in Brianna and Stephan's life. The first half of the book the couple did not even see each other. And each chapter of Stephan at work or Brianna dealing with life away from him seemed to slowly drag. A lot of filler was added throughout these chapters that made the book longer, and I did not necessarily understand the point. <br /><br />However, even though they were apart (which stinks for the reader), it was nice to see Brianna try to learn to function without him. That has been one of my major annoyances throughout these books was how much Brianna had regressed. Fear runs her life frequently. And though she still freaks out on her friends, she slowly begins to show some independence and willpower. And has a couple of moments were she begins taking charge of her life choices even against opposition.<br /><br />This is also seen when Stephan and Brianna finally do get together, she begins to have more confidence, playfulness, and willingness to learn. Even though Brianna has been through a lot, Stephan still wants her to be his sub. Which has really aggravated me at points in the previous ones, however in this book he makes it clear that if she never reaches that point that is okay. And while he clearly still wants that type of relationship, he does not pressure her or demand that she submit. <br /><br />When Anna goes to trial against the man that abused her. The author did an amazing job capturing the emotions that she and Stephen were feeling. Everything here felt emotional and realistic. It was not easy for her or the reader to reaccount all of the horrific things that Anna had experienced. <br /><br />I wanted a bit more from the epilogue, but was satisfied with the ending. Besides some of the fillers (and keeping the main characters apart for so long), this book ties up the ending nicely. This is an intense series to experience with the main character being the subject of abuse and then rescued by a gentle (yet still very alpha, and yes he is filthy rich) dominant. <br /><br />I would not recommend for everyone. However, if your are wanting an emotional ride and journey (you will feel protective over Anna, I did) then give this series a try.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><i><br />*This copy was kindly provided by the publisher via NetGalley in exchange for an honest review.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="7405339985745948912" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


